66
00:06:03,863 --> 00:06:05,194
Sit.

67
00:06:08,301 --> 00:06:10,235
[Birds chirping]

68
00:06:10,303 --> 00:06:13,966
[Vehicle approaches]

69
00:06:16,242 --> 00:06:18,335
[Engine turns off]

70
00:06:18,411 --> 00:06:20,675
[Doors close]

71
00:06:25,084 --> 00:06:28,383
The imperfect subjunctive,
like the imperfect indicative,

72
00:06:28,454 --> 00:06:31,048
indicates action in the past.

73
00:06:31,124 --> 00:06:35,220
[Translation]
He wanted her to give him
the money.

74
00:06:35,294 --> 00:06:37,159
Translate, somebody.

75
00:06:37,230 --> 00:06:38,390
Quickly.

76
00:06:38,464 --> 00:06:40,227
He wanted her to give him
some money.

77
00:06:40,299 --> 00:06:41,732
Put up your hand.

78
00:06:41,801 --> 00:06:45,202
I will not have girls talking
out of turn in my class.

79
00:06:45,271 --> 00:06:47,967
[Door opens, chairs shift]

80
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:49,803
Good morning, girls.

81
00:06:49,876 --> 00:06:51,935
Girls:
Good morning, Miss Stewart.

82
00:06:52,011 --> 00:06:55,572
Sit.

83
00:06:55,648 --> 00:07:02,383
Miss Waller, class...
this is Juliet Hulme.

84
00:07:05,758 --> 00:07:08,249
Juliet is joining us
from St. Margaret,

85
00:07:08,327 --> 00:07:10,158
and prior to that,
she spent some time

86
00:07:10,229 --> 00:07:12,424
at Queenswood
in the Hawkes Bay.

87
00:07:12,498 --> 00:07:14,693
I am actually from England,
Miss Stewart.

88
00:07:14,767 --> 00:07:15,927
Of course.

89
00:07:16,002 --> 00:07:18,470
Juliet's father is
Dr. Hulme,

90
00:07:18,538 --> 00:07:20,768
rector
of Canterbury College.

91
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:24,503
Juliet has traveled
all over the world.

92
00:07:24,577 --> 00:07:27,546
And I'm sure she's very eager
to share her impressions

93
00:07:27,613 --> 00:07:32,516
of exotic lands across the seas
with the girls of 3A.

94
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:35,645
Hmm. Well, I'll leave you to it,
Miss Waller.

95
00:07:35,721 --> 00:07:38,315
Juliet.

96
00:07:38,391 --> 00:07:39,688
[Door closes]

97
00:07:39,759 --> 00:07:41,954
Miss Waller; You can
sit over here, Juliet.

98
00:07:45,531 --> 00:07:49,433
We use French names
in this class.

99
00:07:49,502 --> 00:07:52,232
You can choose your own.

100
00:07:52,305 --> 00:07:55,638
Now, irregular verbs
in the present subjunctive...

101
00:07:55,708 --> 00:08:02,443
[Translation]
I doubted... that he would come.

102
00:08:02,515 --> 00:08:06,383
Excuse me, Miss Waller.
You've made a mistake.

103
00:08:06,452 --> 00:08:10,855
[Translation]
"I doubted that he would
come" is, in fact,
the spoken subjunctive.

104
00:08:10,923 --> 00:08:14,791
It is customary to stand
when addressing a teacher...

105
00:08:14,861 --> 00:08:16,351
Antoinette.

106
00:08:19,765 --> 00:08:21,733
You should have written
[Translation] "came."

107
00:08:21,801 --> 00:08:23,393
Oh.

108
00:08:23,469 --> 00:08:27,496
L-I must have copied it
incorrectly from my notes.

109
00:08:27,573 --> 00:08:30,167
You don't need to apologize,
Miss Waller.

110
00:08:30,243 --> 00:08:32,507
I found it frightfully
difficult myself

111
00:08:32,578 --> 00:08:34,341
until I got
the hang of it.

112
00:08:34,413 --> 00:08:36,847
[Angrily]
Thank you, Juliet.

113
00:08:36,916 --> 00:08:41,285
Open your textbook
to page 17.

114
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:49,990
Right, I thought we'd do
some life drawing today,

115
00:08:50,062 --> 00:08:51,757
so why don't you pair off
into twos

116
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:54,197
and decide who wants to model
and who wants to draw?

117
00:08:54,267 --> 00:08:58,897
[Indistinct conversations]

118
00:08:58,971 --> 00:09:01,405
Oh, Juliet,
you haven't got a partner.

119
00:09:01,474 --> 00:09:03,305
Oh, that's all right,
Mrs. Collins.

120
00:09:03,376 --> 00:09:05,241
I'm sure I can manage
without one.

121
00:09:07,246 --> 00:09:10,545
Pauline,
are you with anybody?

122
00:09:10,616 --> 00:09:11,878
Good.

123
00:09:11,951 --> 00:09:15,785
You can come up here
and pair up with Juliet.

124
00:09:19,191 --> 00:09:21,682
Draw some heavier
lines there.

125
00:09:31,037 --> 00:09:34,495
You might want to
change the color.
Make it a bit darker.

126
00:09:34,574 --> 00:09:36,940
That's very nice,
Joanne.

127
00:09:37,009 --> 00:09:40,137
Good heavens, Juliet.

128
00:09:40,212 --> 00:09:42,442
What on Earth is this?

129
00:09:42,515 --> 00:09:44,745
St. George and the dragon.

130
00:09:44,817 --> 00:09:46,284
Where's Pauline?

131
00:09:46,352 --> 00:09:48,513
Oh, I haven't gotten around
to drawing her yet.

132
00:09:48,588 --> 00:09:50,180
I was going to pop her
on a rock,

133
00:09:50,256 --> 00:09:51,848
but I seem to have run out
of room.

134
00:09:51,924 --> 00:09:53,186
Sorry.

135
00:09:53,259 --> 00:09:56,092
I don't know if you've
noticed, Mrs. Collins,

136
00:09:56,162 --> 00:09:58,926
but I've actually drawn
St. George in the likeness

137
00:09:58,998 --> 00:10:02,263
of the world's greatest tenor,
Mario Lanza.

138
00:10:02,335 --> 00:10:05,099
Yes, I know.
It's very clever, Juliet.

139
00:10:05,171 --> 00:10:07,935
But when I set you a topic,
I expect you to follow it.

140
00:10:08,007 --> 00:10:09,998
Now, put that down
and start again.

141
00:10:16,415 --> 00:10:19,714
I think
your drawing's fantastic.

142
00:10:23,322 --> 00:10:25,813
[Vehicles passing]

143
00:10:25,891 --> 00:10:27,825
Ooh. Mackerel.

144
00:10:27,893 --> 00:10:30,327
Well, we'll have them
for lunch tomorrow.

145
00:10:30,396 --> 00:10:33,661
Oh, let's have them now while
they're fresh, eh, Honora?

146
00:10:33,733 --> 00:10:35,098
Well,
I think you'll find

147
00:10:35,167 --> 00:10:37,499
our Mr. Bayliss isn't
too keen on seafood,

148
00:10:37,570 --> 00:10:40,061
and I've got lamb chops
in the refrigerator.

149
00:10:41,574 --> 00:10:43,337
Excuse me.

150
00:10:43,409 --> 00:10:46,173
Would you mind if I put
my new long-playing record on?

151
00:10:46,245 --> 00:10:48,975
You're partial to
a nice bit of mackerel,
aren't you, Steve?

152
00:10:49,048 --> 00:10:52,484
Uh, well, actually, I'm not much
of a fish man, Mr. Rieper.

153
00:10:52,551 --> 00:10:55,816
Oh, you have been
splashing out.

154
00:10:55,888 --> 00:10:59,051
Oh, it's all right!
I've got my board money.

155
00:10:59,125 --> 00:11:00,217
[Door opens]

156
00:11:00,292 --> 00:11:01,554
Hello.

157
00:11:01,627 --> 00:11:02,719
[Door closes]

158
00:11:02,795 --> 00:11:04,695
Well? Tell us.

159
00:11:04,764 --> 00:11:05,856
How'd you go?

160
00:11:05,931 --> 00:11:07,523
Got an "A," Mum.

161
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:09,727
Oh.

162
00:11:09,802 --> 00:11:12,635
Oh, don't worry about it now.
We'll sort it out after dinner.

163
00:11:12,705 --> 00:11:14,229
You go and put
your record on.

164
00:11:14,306 --> 00:11:15,739
Doris Day.

165
00:11:15,808 --> 00:11:18,675
I think
she's really talented.

166
00:11:18,744 --> 00:11:22,236
["Be My Love" plays]

167
00:11:25,151 --> 00:11:27,415
Got to be quick
in this house, mate.

168
00:11:27,486 --> 00:11:37,361
(music) Be my love for no one else
can end this yearning (music)

169
00:11:37,430 --> 00:11:41,196
(music) This need
that you and you alone... (music)

170
00:11:41,267 --> 00:11:44,395
Hey, isn't that
that famous Irish singer,

171
00:11:44,470 --> 00:11:46,301
Murray O'Lanza?

172
00:11:46,372 --> 00:11:48,636
He's Italian, Dad.

173
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:51,199
The world's greatest tenor.

174
00:11:51,277 --> 00:11:55,543
(music)... the dreams
that you inspire (music)

175
00:11:55,614 --> 00:12:02,281
(music) With every sweet desire (music)

176
00:12:02,354 --> 00:12:06,017
- [Lip-syncing]
- (music) Be my love (music)

177
00:12:06,092 --> 00:12:12,827
(music) And with your kisses
set me burning (music)

178
00:12:12,898 --> 00:12:14,160
Stop it!

179
00:12:14,233 --> 00:12:18,465
(music) One kiss is all I need
to seal... (music)

180
00:12:18,537 --> 00:12:20,300
You're spoiling it!

181
00:12:20,372 --> 00:12:22,966
(music) And hand in hand (music)

182
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:24,942
- Oop! [Laughs]
- (music) You'll find (music)

183
00:12:25,010 --> 00:12:26,637
- Go away!
- (music) Love's promised land (music)

184
00:12:26,712 --> 00:12:30,273
(music) There'll be no one
but you... (music)

185
00:12:30,349 --> 00:12:33,910
And left...

186
00:12:33,986 --> 00:12:35,078
right...

187
00:12:35,154 --> 00:12:36,485
and left...

188
00:12:36,555 --> 00:12:38,352
and right...

189
00:12:38,424 --> 00:12:40,085
and left...

190
00:12:43,429 --> 00:12:45,590
One...

191
00:12:45,664 --> 00:12:47,325
two...

192
00:12:47,399 --> 00:12:49,333
Can I have another look?

193
00:12:49,401 --> 00:12:52,495
One...

194
00:12:52,571 --> 00:12:55,131
Lift those legs high,
girls,

195
00:12:55,207 --> 00:12:57,801
keeping those legs straight.

196
00:12:57,877 --> 00:12:59,435
One...

197
00:12:59,512 --> 00:13:03,278
[Gasps]

198
00:13:03,349 --> 00:13:06,614
That's so impressive.

199
00:13:06,685 --> 00:13:08,676
Can I touch it?

200
00:13:08,754 --> 00:13:12,520
Carry on now.
You're doing well.

201
00:13:12,591 --> 00:13:15,719
[Inhales sharply,
shudders]

202
00:13:20,366 --> 00:13:24,302
I've got scars.
They're on my lungs.

203
00:13:24,370 --> 00:13:27,339
I spent months in bed
during the war,

204
00:13:27,406 --> 00:13:29,670
ravaged by respiratory
illness.

205
00:13:29,742 --> 00:13:32,734
Mummy and Daddy sent me
to the Bahamas to recuperate.

206
00:13:32,812 --> 00:13:34,609
I didn't see them
for five years.

207
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:36,170
But we're together now,

208
00:13:36,248 --> 00:13:38,842
and Mummy's promised
they'll never leave me again.

209
00:13:38,918 --> 00:13:42,547
Pauline; I spent ages in
hospital, too, with my leg.

210
00:13:42,621 --> 00:13:45,215
I had to have
all these operations.

211
00:13:45,291 --> 00:13:48,920
Osteomyelitis turns
your bones to chalk.

212
00:13:48,994 --> 00:13:53,090
Took them two years to
drain all the muck out.

213
00:13:53,165 --> 00:13:55,258
Cheer up.

214
00:13:55,334 --> 00:13:59,293
All the best people
have bad chests and
bone diseases.

215
00:13:59,371 --> 00:14:02,534
It's all
frightfully romantic.

216
00:14:02,708 --> 00:14:05,700
[Birds chirping]

217
00:14:20,626 --> 00:14:23,993
[Chirping continues]

218
00:14:31,837 --> 00:14:34,203
[Juliet laughing]

219
00:14:42,047 --> 00:14:45,539
[Laughter continues]

220
00:14:45,618 --> 00:14:49,611
Oh! Hi, Paul!
[Giggles]

221
00:14:50,689 --> 00:14:52,122
- Aah!
- Oh!

222
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:54,890
The evil Prince Runnymede
is escaping!

223
00:14:54,960 --> 00:14:57,053
Aah!

224
00:14:57,129 --> 00:14:58,619
Get him, Paul!

225
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,333
[Breathing heavily]

226
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:10,898
Faster!

227
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:19,913
[Laughing]

228
00:15:22,655 --> 00:15:24,316
Come on!

229
00:15:26,759 --> 00:15:28,192
Aah!

230
00:15:30,229 --> 00:15:31,787
[Laughs]

231
00:15:33,732 --> 00:15:36,758
[Leaves rustling]

232
00:15:38,203 --> 00:15:40,137
[Breathing heavily]

233
00:15:40,205 --> 00:15:42,139
The blighter's gone
to ground!

234
00:15:42,207 --> 00:15:43,697
[Exhales deeply]

235
00:15:43,776 --> 00:15:46,438
- Aah!
- Ahh!

236
00:15:46,512 --> 00:15:48,173
Oh, God, Jonesy!

237
00:15:48,247 --> 00:15:49,339
Jonesy, stop it!

238
00:15:49,415 --> 00:15:50,848
[Breathing heavily]

239
00:15:50,916 --> 00:15:53,214
Leave her alone,
you rotten little turd!

240
00:15:53,285 --> 00:15:54,479
But she's an invader!

241
00:15:54,553 --> 00:15:56,418
Go away.
We're not playing anymore.

242
00:15:56,488 --> 00:15:58,456
Go on.
Bugger off.

243
00:15:58,524 --> 00:16:00,958
You said a swearword.
I'm telling Mummy on you.

244
00:16:01,026 --> 00:16:04,518
And I'm going into
your bedroom to break
every one of your toys.

245
00:16:09,134 --> 00:16:10,897
[Both grunt]

246
00:16:10,970 --> 00:16:12,733
I'm sorry.

247
00:16:12,805 --> 00:16:13,863
Oh!

248
00:16:13,939 --> 00:16:15,429
Oh, God!

249
00:16:19,611 --> 00:16:21,203
I'm so sorry.

250
00:16:21,280 --> 00:16:23,748
It doesn't matter.

251
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:25,909
Of course it matters!

252
00:16:25,985 --> 00:16:27,976
It's Mario.

253
00:16:31,223 --> 00:16:33,214
[Sniffing]

254
00:16:41,667 --> 00:16:43,658
What on Earth are these?

255
00:16:45,871 --> 00:16:48,203
They're egg-and-salmon
sandwiches,

256
00:16:48,273 --> 00:16:50,673
and I gave them to you
several days ago.

257
00:16:50,743 --> 00:16:52,506
Oh.

258
00:16:52,578 --> 00:16:55,513
Yeah, I thought
I could smell sulfur.

259
00:16:55,581 --> 00:16:59,517
God, Henry.
You're hopeless!

260
00:16:59,585 --> 00:17:02,577
Can't be trusted
with anything as simple
as lunch.

261
00:17:02,654 --> 00:17:04,918
Mother!

262
00:17:04,990 --> 00:17:06,981
Oh... [laughs] hello.

263
00:17:07,059 --> 00:17:10,119
Mother, Jonesy broke
Paul's record!

264
00:17:10,195 --> 00:17:11,958
Oh, dear.

265
00:17:12,031 --> 00:17:13,794
We must buy her another one.

266
00:17:13,866 --> 00:17:17,165
Would you like
a cup of tea... Paul?

267
00:17:17,236 --> 00:17:20,535
Um, no, thank you.

268
00:17:20,606 --> 00:17:24,337
Well, Juliet's told us
all about you.

269
00:17:24,410 --> 00:17:27,277
I hear you're very fond
of opera.

270
00:17:27,346 --> 00:17:30,076
Now,
which one shall we play?

271
00:17:30,149 --> 00:17:33,641
Juliet, your father
is trying to study.

272
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:35,277
Daddy can study
while we're playing records.

273
00:17:35,354 --> 00:17:37,413
Why don't you
go back outside, hmm?

274
00:17:37,489 --> 00:17:38,956
I'll be finished soon.

275
00:17:39,024 --> 00:17:41,822
["The Donkey Serenade" plays]

276
00:17:41,894 --> 00:17:43,555
[Juliet laughing]

277
00:17:46,799 --> 00:17:53,602
(music) Hiya-a-a-a-a-a (music)

278
00:17:53,672 --> 00:17:56,106
[Laughing]

279
00:17:56,175 --> 00:17:57,267
[Smooches]

280
00:17:57,342 --> 00:18:04,908
(music) Hiya-a-a-a-a-a-a (music)

281
00:18:04,983 --> 00:18:08,578
(music) There's a song in the air (music)

282
00:18:08,654 --> 00:18:13,921
(music) But the fair senorita
doesn't seem to care (music)

283
00:18:13,992 --> 00:18:19,521
- [Airplane noises]
- (music) For the song in the air (music)

284
00:18:19,598 --> 00:18:23,398
(music) So I'll sing to the mule (music)

285
00:18:23,469 --> 00:18:26,233
(music) If you're sure
she won't think (music)

286
00:18:26,305 --> 00:18:35,373
(music) That I am just a fool
serenading a mule (music)

287
00:18:35,447 --> 00:18:39,611
(music) Amigo mio, does she not have
a dainty bray? (music)

288
00:18:39,685 --> 00:18:43,348
(music) She listens carefully
to each little tune you play (music)

289
00:18:43,422 --> 00:18:44,548
(music) A bella senorita (music)

290
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:47,023
(music) Si, si, mi muchachito (music)

291
00:18:47,092 --> 00:18:50,118
(music) She'd love to sing it, too,
if only she knew the way (music)

292
00:18:50,195 --> 00:18:53,164
(music) But try as she may (music)

293
00:18:53,232 --> 00:18:57,396
(music) In her voice there's a flaw (music)

294
00:18:57,469 --> 00:19:02,566
(music) And all
that the lady can say (music)

295
00:19:02,641 --> 00:19:04,268
Mario!

296
00:19:04,343 --> 00:19:13,877
(music) Is "Heeha-a-a-a-a-w" (music)

297
00:19:13,952 --> 00:19:17,752
(music) Senorita donkey-cita
not so fleet as a mosquito (music)

298
00:19:17,823 --> 00:19:19,415
(music) But so sweet
like my Chiquita (music)

299
00:19:19,491 --> 00:19:21,254
(music) You're the one for me (music)

300
00:19:21,326 --> 00:19:23,226
[Both laughing]

301
00:19:23,295 --> 00:19:26,025
(music) There's a light
in her eyes... (music)

302
00:19:26,098 --> 00:19:27,190
Oh! Oh!

303
00:19:27,266 --> 00:19:28,699
[Both scream]

304
00:19:28,767 --> 00:19:30,928
[Horn blares]

305
00:19:31,003 --> 00:19:33,062
[Screaming]

306
00:19:33,138 --> 00:19:34,070
[Thud]

307
00:19:34,139 --> 00:19:35,936
Paul!

308
00:19:36,008 --> 00:19:39,171
[Breathing heavily]

309
00:19:39,244 --> 00:19:40,336
Oh, God!

310
00:19:40,412 --> 00:19:43,176
Paul,
are you all right?!

311
00:19:43,248 --> 00:19:46,342
I... I think...

312
00:19:46,418 --> 00:19:47,908
I'm dying.

313
00:19:47,986 --> 00:19:49,510
Don't!

314
00:19:49,588 --> 00:19:51,180
- [Coughs]
- Please.

315
00:19:51,256 --> 00:19:53,019
Please don't!

316
00:19:53,091 --> 00:19:55,924
[Coughs, gasps]

317
00:19:55,994 --> 00:19:58,588
[Gasps] Paul!

318
00:19:58,664 --> 00:20:02,600
[Sobs]

319
00:20:02,668 --> 00:20:04,898
- Ugh!
- [Gasps]

320
00:20:04,970 --> 00:20:07,131
You've been eating onions!

321
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:09,401
You toad!

322
00:20:09,474 --> 00:20:11,066
- Oh!
- [Laughing]

323
00:20:11,143 --> 00:20:13,304
[Both laughing]

324
00:20:22,120 --> 00:20:25,715
(music) There's a light
in her eyes (music)

325
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:28,658
Both; (music) Though she may try
to hide it (music)

326
00:20:28,727 --> 00:20:34,563
(music) She cannot deny
there's a light in her eyes (music)

327
00:20:34,633 --> 00:20:39,297
(music) The charm of her smile
so beguiles Don Diego (music)

328
00:20:39,371 --> 00:20:44,900
(music) That he rode a mile
for the charm of her smile (music)

329
00:20:44,977 --> 00:20:46,467
[Both laughing]

330
00:20:51,550 --> 00:20:53,950
- Waaaa!
- Wheeee!

331
00:20:54,019 --> 00:20:57,352
(music) Her face is a dream (music)

332
00:20:57,422 --> 00:21:01,017
(music) Like an angel I saw... (music)

333
00:21:01,093 --> 00:21:03,687
[Sheep bleats in distance]

334
00:21:03,762 --> 00:21:10,531
(music) But all
that my darling can scream (music)

335
00:21:10,602 --> 00:21:19,738
Mario Lanza;
(music) Is "Heeha-a-a-a-a-a-w" (music)

336
00:21:19,811 --> 00:21:23,247
(music) Senorita donkey-cita
not so fleet as a mosquito (music)

337
00:21:23,315 --> 00:21:25,112
(music) But so sweet
like my Chiquita (music)

338
00:21:25,183 --> 00:21:26,616
(music) You're the one for me (music)

339
00:21:26,685 --> 00:21:28,277
Ole!

340
00:21:28,353 --> 00:21:31,186
[Crickets chirping]

341
00:21:48,540 --> 00:21:51,236
Oh, I wish James Mason
would do a religious picture.

342
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:54,074
He'd be perfect as Jesus.

343
00:21:54,146 --> 00:21:55,238
[Sighs]

344
00:21:55,314 --> 00:21:58,044
Daddy says the Bible is
a load of bunkum.

345
00:21:58,116 --> 00:22:00,175
But we're all going
to Heaven.

346
00:22:00,252 --> 00:22:03,380
I'm not.

347
00:22:03,455 --> 00:22:06,151
I'm going
to the Fourth World.

348
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:11,027
It's sort of like Heaven,
only better,

349
00:22:11,096 --> 00:22:14,259
because there aren't
any Christians.

350
00:22:14,333 --> 00:22:17,325
It's an absolute paradise
of music, art,

351
00:22:17,402 --> 00:22:19,370
and pure enjoyment.

352
00:22:20,739 --> 00:22:23,674
James will be there,
and Mario,

353
00:22:23,742 --> 00:22:26,677
only they'll be saints.

354
00:22:26,745 --> 00:22:29,737
St. Mario.

355
00:22:33,452 --> 00:22:37,946
To be known... as "He."

356
00:22:40,192 --> 00:22:42,683
"He."

357
00:22:45,464 --> 00:22:47,227
"Him."

358
00:22:47,299 --> 00:22:48,732
"Him."

359
00:22:50,535 --> 00:22:51,695
"This."

360
00:22:53,338 --> 00:22:55,499
"This."

361
00:23:02,848 --> 00:23:05,248
"That."

362
00:23:05,317 --> 00:23:07,308
"That."

363
00:23:12,824 --> 00:23:15,315
"It."

364
00:23:15,394 --> 00:23:16,827
Absolutely not!

365
00:23:16,895 --> 00:23:20,729
Orson Welles! Ugh!
The most hideous man alive!

366
00:23:24,836 --> 00:23:33,266
We... give praise...
to the saints.

367
00:23:33,345 --> 00:23:35,973
Saints.

368
00:23:42,454 --> 00:23:48,654
[Suspenseful music plays]

369
00:23:48,727 --> 00:23:51,321
[Water rushing]

370
00:23:51,396 --> 00:23:52,454
["Deck the Halls" plays]

371
00:23:52,531 --> 00:23:54,123
Wendy;
Oh, wonderful, Mum!

372
00:23:54,199 --> 00:23:56,759
Herbert; [Gasps] I got
me self a pair of socks!

373
00:23:56,835 --> 00:23:59,804
Honora; Oh, Wendy. Oh.

374
00:24:02,674 --> 00:24:05,006
Oh, thanks.

375
00:24:05,076 --> 00:24:06,668
From Dad.

376
00:24:06,745 --> 00:24:11,079
["Angels We Have Heard on High"
plays]

377
00:24:11,149 --> 00:24:14,744
Mario Lanza!
Oh, thanks, Yvonne.

378
00:24:14,820 --> 00:24:17,414
Herbert;
I hope it's all right.

379
00:24:17,489 --> 00:24:19,980
It's from
Whitcombe & Tombs.

380
00:24:30,702 --> 00:24:33,637
Pauline; I decided
that my New Year's resolution

381
00:24:33,705 --> 00:24:36,868
is to be more lenient
with others.

382
00:24:36,942 --> 00:24:39,536
Pikelets! Yum!

383
00:24:39,611 --> 00:24:41,203
Aren't you going out?

384
00:24:41,279 --> 00:24:42,678
Not until 2:30.

385
00:24:42,747 --> 00:24:45,580
This is a private function.
Go away!

386
00:24:47,786 --> 00:24:49,219
[Doorbell rings]

387
00:24:49,287 --> 00:24:50,777
Oh! Come on.

388
00:24:50,856 --> 00:24:53,120
- Sausage rolls.
- Herbert; Come on through.

389
00:24:53,191 --> 00:24:55,250
Look who I found.

390
00:24:58,997 --> 00:25:01,488
Hello... Juliet.

391
00:25:01,566 --> 00:25:04,501
Hello, Mrs. Rieper.

392
00:25:09,140 --> 00:25:11,904
It's so nice to meet you.

393
00:25:16,615 --> 00:25:19,175
And so,
in a blazing fury,

394
00:25:19,251 --> 00:25:21,412
Charles runs
Lancelot Trelawney through

395
00:25:21,486 --> 00:25:24,580
with his sword, leaving
Deborah free to accept

396
00:25:24,656 --> 00:25:27,056
Charles' proposal
of marriage.

397
00:25:27,125 --> 00:25:28,456
[Sighs, chuckles]

398
00:25:34,266 --> 00:25:37,064
I've heard your mother
on 3 YA.

399
00:25:37,135 --> 00:25:39,899
The Women's Session has
lots of lively debate.

400
00:25:39,971 --> 00:25:42,405
Well, actually,
Mummy's left that program now.

401
00:25:42,474 --> 00:25:45,272
She's far too busy with
the Marriage Guidance Council.

402
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:47,243
They sound like
a queer mob.

403
00:25:47,312 --> 00:25:48,643
Dad.

404
00:25:48,713 --> 00:25:51,443
I wouldn't want my private
business being discussed

405
00:25:51,516 --> 00:25:53,040
with a complete stranger.

406
00:25:53,118 --> 00:25:55,814
Oh, no.
Mummy's awfully good at it.

407
00:25:55,887 --> 00:25:58,378
She has deep discussions
with unhappy couples

408
00:25:58,456 --> 00:26:00,822
and persuades them to give it
another go.

409
00:26:00,892 --> 00:26:04,225
In two years,
she's only had four divorces.

410
00:26:04,296 --> 00:26:07,231
She should really be working
for the U.N.

411
00:26:09,134 --> 00:26:13,230
My wife's blaming me.
Says it's all my fault.

412
00:26:13,305 --> 00:26:17,503
And how do you feel
about that, Mr. Perry?

413
00:26:17,576 --> 00:26:21,273
Please... call me Bill.

414
00:26:24,683 --> 00:26:27,481
I don't know what went wrong.
My wife feels that, uh...

415
00:26:27,552 --> 00:26:30,817
Oh, no. No.

416
00:26:30,889 --> 00:26:36,327
Let's talk about
your feelings... Bill.

417
00:26:36,394 --> 00:26:41,297
Mummy's got a special technique
called "deep therapy."

418
00:26:41,366 --> 00:26:42,424
What's that?

419
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:43,660
I'm not sure,

420
00:26:43,735 --> 00:26:45,999
but it's proving to be
very popular.

421
00:26:46,071 --> 00:26:47,834
[Doorbell rings]

422
00:26:47,906 --> 00:26:49,168
Mmm.

423
00:26:49,240 --> 00:26:51,299
Eat up, Yvonne.

424
00:26:53,244 --> 00:26:55,508
It's my middle name.

425
00:26:55,580 --> 00:26:59,311
Yvonne tells us you're...
you're good at making models.

426
00:26:59,384 --> 00:27:02,182
I adore anything
to do with the arts.

427
00:27:02,253 --> 00:27:04,414
Well, we're...
we're pretty handy

428
00:27:04,489 --> 00:27:06,650
with the old model
making, too, eh?

429
00:27:06,725 --> 00:27:10,456
I've never cottoned on
to plasticine like you girls,

430
00:27:10,528 --> 00:27:13,053
but I enjoy making
anything out of wood.

431
00:27:13,131 --> 00:27:16,464
Oh. Are you a carpenter,
Mr. Rieper?

432
00:27:16,534 --> 00:27:18,968
I work at Dennis Brothers...
fish supply.

433
00:27:19,037 --> 00:27:22,029
He's the manager.

434
00:27:22,107 --> 00:27:25,042
This is the dining room.
Do excuse us.

435
00:27:25,110 --> 00:27:27,544
Um, breakfast is between
7:00 and 9:00.

436
00:27:27,612 --> 00:27:29,307
The bedrooms are small,

437
00:27:29,381 --> 00:27:32,407
but they're very clean
and comfortable.

438
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:33,678
[Door opens]

439
00:27:33,752 --> 00:27:35,743
This, um,
this story of yours...

440
00:27:35,820 --> 00:27:38,812
perhaps the school
newspaper will print it
when it's finished.

441
00:27:38,890 --> 00:27:42,986
Actually, Mr. Rieper,
it's a novel.

442
00:27:43,061 --> 00:27:44,995
And we'll be sending it
to New York.

443
00:27:45,063 --> 00:27:47,691
That's where all the big
publishing houses are based.

444
00:27:47,766 --> 00:27:49,893
Is that a fact?
[Chuckles]

445
00:27:49,968 --> 00:27:52,937
Well, you'd better put me name
down for an advance copy.

446
00:27:57,308 --> 00:28:00,744
Pauline; We have decided
how sad it is for other people

447
00:28:00,812 --> 00:28:03,406
that they cannot appreciate
our genius,

448
00:28:03,481 --> 00:28:05,005
but we hope the book

449
00:28:05,083 --> 00:28:07,745
will help them
to do so a little,

450
00:28:07,819 --> 00:28:11,755
though no one
could fully appreciate us.

451
00:28:11,890 --> 00:28:16,691
(music) How much is that doggie
in the window (music)

452
00:28:16,761 --> 00:28:18,092
Woof, woof.

453
00:28:18,163 --> 00:28:23,362
(music) The one with
the waggly tail? (music)

454
00:28:23,435 --> 00:28:27,166
(music) How much is that doggie
in the window? (music)

455
00:28:27,238 --> 00:28:29,103
- Oh, go on.
- Woof, woof.

456
00:28:29,174 --> 00:28:32,974
(music) I do hope
that doggie's for sale (music)

457
00:28:33,044 --> 00:28:34,909
Juliet; California,
California verse.

458
00:28:34,979 --> 00:28:38,972
(music) I must take a trip
to California (music)

459
00:28:39,050 --> 00:28:44,420
(music) And leave
my poor sweetheart alone (music)

460
00:28:44,489 --> 00:28:46,821
[Laughter]

461
00:28:53,798 --> 00:28:56,289
Aah! Aah!
[Laughing]

462
00:28:58,002 --> 00:29:01,233
- Aah!
- Ahhhhh!

463
00:29:01,306 --> 00:29:03,069
[Screaming]

464
00:29:03,141 --> 00:29:05,405
[Birds chirping]

465
00:29:05,477 --> 00:29:07,638
[Camera shutter clicking]

466
00:29:10,048 --> 00:29:12,141
Pauline; Charles clutches
his wounded shoulder

467
00:29:12,217 --> 00:29:14,845
- [Horse whinnies, gallops]
- As he gallops
into the courtyard!

468
00:29:14,919 --> 00:29:17,888
Deborah awaits his return
in their private boudoir

469
00:29:17,956 --> 00:29:19,116
at the very top
of the tower!

470
00:29:19,190 --> 00:29:21,954
He smells her scent
from 50 paces

471
00:29:22,026 --> 00:29:24,426
and urges his steed
onward!

472
00:29:24,496 --> 00:29:26,430
[Hoofbeat]

473
00:29:26,498 --> 00:29:28,227
He flings open the door

474
00:29:28,299 --> 00:29:30,893
and launches himself
at the bed,

475
00:29:30,969 --> 00:29:32,493
ravishing her!

476
00:29:32,570 --> 00:29:34,162
Oh, God, yes!

477
00:29:34,239 --> 00:29:37,003
I bet she gets
up the duff on their
first night together.

478
00:29:37,075 --> 00:29:38,702
What's "up the duff"?

479
00:29:38,777 --> 00:29:41,974
Something
you wouldn't understand.

480
00:29:42,046 --> 00:29:43,604
- Ugh!
- Ahhhh!

481
00:29:43,681 --> 00:29:46,275
Tell me!
I'm almost 10!

482
00:29:46,351 --> 00:29:49,115
You're 81/2
and incredibly stupid!

483
00:29:49,187 --> 00:29:50,449
[Laughter]

484
00:29:53,391 --> 00:29:56,121
Mummy...
Paul and I have decided

485
00:29:56,194 --> 00:29:59,391
that Charles and Deborah
are going to have a baby,

486
00:29:59,464 --> 00:30:01,796
an heir to the throne
of Borovnia.

487
00:30:01,866 --> 00:30:04,596
What a splendid idea.

488
00:30:04,669 --> 00:30:06,398
We're calling him
Diello.

489
00:30:06,471 --> 00:30:10,168
Well, that's
a good dramatic name.

490
00:30:10,241 --> 00:30:12,471
Paul thought it up.

491
00:30:12,544 --> 00:30:17,004
Aren't you clever?
Hmm.

492
00:30:17,081 --> 00:30:20,414
There... all done.

493
00:30:23,087 --> 00:30:25,021
[Laughter]

494
00:30:25,089 --> 00:30:27,649
Oh, look at you two...

495
00:30:27,725 --> 00:30:29,716
A couple
of Borovnian Princesses

496
00:30:29,794 --> 00:30:31,762
[Laughing]
If ever I saw them.

497
00:30:31,830 --> 00:30:33,991
[Both laugh]

498
00:30:34,065 --> 00:30:36,556
My daughter...

499
00:30:36,634 --> 00:30:40,070
and my... foster daughter.

500
00:30:40,138 --> 00:30:42,299
[Both sigh]

501
00:30:45,743 --> 00:30:47,836
Hilda,
I can't find that letter

502
00:30:47,912 --> 00:30:49,436
from the High Commission.

503
00:30:49,514 --> 00:30:51,914
They want
our passport numbers.

504
00:30:51,983 --> 00:30:53,917
Are you going abroad,
Daddy?

505
00:30:53,985 --> 00:30:57,284
Your father's attending
a university conference
in England, darling.

506
00:30:57,355 --> 00:30:59,380
We'll only be gone
for a few weeks.

507
00:30:59,457 --> 00:31:02,585
You're not going,
are you, Mummy?

508
00:31:02,660 --> 00:31:05,458
Well, yes,
l-I thought I might.

509
00:31:05,530 --> 00:31:07,327
It's, uh, a long time

510
00:31:07,398 --> 00:31:09,525
for your father and I
to be apart.

511
00:31:09,601 --> 00:31:12,764
But I should go, too.

512
00:31:12,837 --> 00:31:14,270
Darling,
you've got school.

513
00:31:14,339 --> 00:31:15,806
You've only
just settled in.

514
00:31:15,874 --> 00:31:17,569
B-But...

515
00:31:17,642 --> 00:31:20,770
Who's coming
to the shops?

516
00:31:20,845 --> 00:31:23,040
Me! I'm coming!

517
00:31:23,114 --> 00:31:25,912
I need some cigarettes.

518
00:31:25,984 --> 00:31:29,010
Put on your shoes,
Jonathon!

519
00:31:36,961 --> 00:31:40,158
[Juliet sobbing]

520
00:31:43,635 --> 00:31:46,763
[Panting]

521
00:31:46,838 --> 00:31:47,964
Oh!

522
00:31:50,108 --> 00:31:52,838
Julie!

523
00:31:55,046 --> 00:31:57,844
Julie!

524
00:31:57,916 --> 00:32:00,578
Julie!

525
00:32:00,652 --> 00:32:03,177
Julie!

526
00:32:03,254 --> 00:32:06,189
[Crying]

527
00:32:21,839 --> 00:32:23,773
[Exhales sharply]

528
00:32:23,841 --> 00:32:25,968
[Gasps] Look, Paul!

529
00:32:26,044 --> 00:32:27,306
What?

530
00:32:27,378 --> 00:32:30,211
- Look!
- What?

531
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:33,717
[Panting]
Oh, it's so beautiful.

532
00:32:33,785 --> 00:32:35,184
What?!

533
00:32:35,253 --> 00:32:38,780
[Crying]
Oh, it's so beautiful!

534
00:32:38,856 --> 00:32:40,949
Pretty flowers.

535
00:32:41,025 --> 00:32:43,550
[Gasping]

536
00:32:45,463 --> 00:32:49,524
[Breathing deeply]

537
00:32:52,570 --> 00:32:54,731
Come with me!

538
00:33:03,514 --> 00:33:04,981
[Thunder rumbles]

539
00:33:05,049 --> 00:33:06,482
[Both gasp]

540
00:33:09,087 --> 00:33:13,421
It's all right.
You'll see.

541
00:33:13,491 --> 00:33:16,551
[Both gasp]

542
00:33:16,627 --> 00:33:19,095
Come on!
Come on!

543
00:33:19,163 --> 00:33:21,996
[Laughter]

544
00:33:29,007 --> 00:33:34,912
[Birds chirping,
water flowing]

545
00:33:34,979 --> 00:33:37,573
[Gasps] Look!

546
00:33:40,918 --> 00:33:43,853
Oh! Oh!

547
00:33:46,824 --> 00:33:49,418
[Birds chirping]

548
00:33:52,296 --> 00:33:55,231
[Laughter]

549
00:33:55,299 --> 00:33:58,291
Pauline; Today
Juliet and I discovered

550
00:33:58,369 --> 00:34:00,428
the key to the Fourth World.

551
00:34:00,505 --> 00:34:03,099
We have had it
in our possession

552
00:34:03,174 --> 00:34:04,801
for about six months,

553
00:34:04,876 --> 00:34:06,639
but we only realized it

554
00:34:06,711 --> 00:34:09,441
on the day
of the death of Christ.

555
00:34:09,514 --> 00:34:12,506
We saw a gateway
through the clouds.

556
00:34:12,583 --> 00:34:15,746
Everything
was full of peace and bliss.

557
00:34:15,820 --> 00:34:20,120
We then realized
we had the key.

558
00:34:20,191 --> 00:34:23,592
We now know we're not genii,
as we thought.

559
00:34:23,661 --> 00:34:26,494
We have an extra part
of our brain

560
00:34:26,564 --> 00:34:29,590
that can appreciate
the Fourth World.

561
00:34:29,667 --> 00:34:31,862
Only about 10 people have it.

562
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:35,394
When we die, we will go
to the Fourth World,

563
00:34:35,473 --> 00:34:38,567
but meanwhile,
on two days every year,

564
00:34:38,643 --> 00:34:40,110
we may use the key

565
00:34:40,178 --> 00:34:43,011
and look into
that beautiful world

566
00:34:43,081 --> 00:34:46,175
which we have been lucky enough
to be allowed to know of

567
00:34:46,250 --> 00:34:49,344
on this day
of finding the key

568
00:34:49,420 --> 00:34:53,356
to the way
through the clouds.

569
00:34:53,458 --> 00:34:56,393
Ughhhhhh!

570
00:34:56,427 --> 00:34:58,190
Push!

571
00:34:58,262 --> 00:34:59,854
[Panting]

572
00:34:59,931 --> 00:35:01,660
It's coming!

573
00:35:01,732 --> 00:35:03,791
Mnhhhhhh!

574
00:35:03,868 --> 00:35:05,768
Oh, God!

575
00:35:05,837 --> 00:35:09,102
[Panting]

576
00:35:09,173 --> 00:35:11,903
It's a boy!

577
00:35:11,976 --> 00:35:13,910
Oh!

578
00:35:13,978 --> 00:35:15,639
Deborah...

579
00:35:15,713 --> 00:35:17,647
[Breathing deeply]

580
00:35:17,715 --> 00:35:20,479
We have a son and heir.

581
00:35:20,551 --> 00:35:24,578
[Sighs deeply]
I shall call him Diello!

582
00:35:24,655 --> 00:35:28,455
Oh, you're
such an incredible woman!

583
00:35:28,526 --> 00:35:32,860
I couldn't have done it
without you, Charles.

584
00:35:32,930 --> 00:35:35,728
The empress Deborah

585
00:35:35,800 --> 00:35:37,825
has the most enormous
difficulty

586
00:35:37,902 --> 00:35:39,335
fending off her husband,

587
00:35:39,403 --> 00:35:41,530
who tries
to have his way with her

588
00:35:41,606 --> 00:35:43,073
morning, noon, and night.

589
00:35:43,141 --> 00:35:45,632
[Laughter]

590
00:35:45,710 --> 00:35:47,234
[Laughter stops]

591
00:35:47,311 --> 00:35:48,801
Thank you, Juliet.

592
00:35:48,880 --> 00:35:50,142
[Coughs]

593
00:35:50,214 --> 00:35:52,842
However...

594
00:35:52,917 --> 00:35:55,010
the queen's biggest problem

595
00:35:55,086 --> 00:35:57,486
is her renegade child, Diello,
who has proven to be

596
00:35:57,555 --> 00:35:59,216
an uncontrollable
little blighter

597
00:35:59,290 --> 00:36:01,884
who slaughters his nannies
whenever the fancy takes him!

598
00:36:01,959 --> 00:36:03,426
That's enough, Juliet!

599
00:36:03,494 --> 00:36:05,189
[Coughs]

600
00:36:05,263 --> 00:36:07,697
I suppose this is
your idea of a joke!

601
00:36:07,765 --> 00:36:09,027
No, Mrs. Stevens.

602
00:36:09,100 --> 00:36:11,398
I suppose you think it
witty and clever

603
00:36:11,469 --> 00:36:12,868
to mock the royal family,

604
00:36:12,937 --> 00:36:15,667
to poke fun at the queen
and the empire

605
00:36:15,740 --> 00:36:18,004
with this... rubbish!

606
00:36:18,075 --> 00:36:19,872
It's not rubbish!

607
00:36:19,944 --> 00:36:21,912
Sit down, Pauline!

608
00:36:21,979 --> 00:36:24,607
[Coughs]
I really don't understand

609
00:36:24,682 --> 00:36:26,980
why you are so upset,
Mrs. Stevens.

610
00:36:27,051 --> 00:36:29,849
I merely wrote an essay
on the royal family,

611
00:36:29,921 --> 00:36:31,115
as requested.

612
00:36:31,189 --> 00:36:33,749
It doesn't say
it has to be the Windsors!

613
00:36:33,824 --> 00:36:34,620
Sit down!

614
00:36:34,692 --> 00:36:36,922
[Coughs]

615
00:36:36,994 --> 00:36:39,929
A girl like you should be
setting an example.

616
00:36:39,997 --> 00:36:41,589
To your seat.

617
00:36:41,666 --> 00:36:43,600
[Coughing]

618
00:36:48,306 --> 00:36:50,706
[Coughing continues]

619
00:36:55,546 --> 00:36:57,411
Stop it, Juliet!

620
00:37:01,986 --> 00:37:04,113
[Spitting up]

621
00:37:06,290 --> 00:37:09,418
Pauline; Mrs. Hulme told me
they had found out today

622
00:37:09,493 --> 00:37:14,362
that Juliet has tuberculosis
on one lung.

623
00:37:14,432 --> 00:37:16,764
Poor Juliet.

624
00:37:16,834 --> 00:37:20,099
I nearly fainted
when I heard.

625
00:37:20,171 --> 00:37:23,607
I had a terrible job
not to cry.

626
00:37:23,674 --> 00:37:26,165
I spent a wretched night.

627
00:37:26,244 --> 00:37:28,405
It would be wonderful

628
00:37:28,479 --> 00:37:31,277
if I could get
tuberculosis, too.

629
00:37:31,349 --> 00:37:32,407
[Door hinges creak]

630
00:37:32,483 --> 00:37:34,075
Come on, sit up.

631
00:37:34,151 --> 00:37:35,413
I'm not hungry.

632
00:37:35,486 --> 00:37:37,113
Oh, Yvonne,
you've got to eat.

633
00:37:37,188 --> 00:37:39,122
You hardly ate any dinner
last night.

634
00:37:39,190 --> 00:37:40,589
Now, come on.

635
00:37:40,658 --> 00:37:43,354
I'm not having you
falling ill.

636
00:37:43,427 --> 00:37:45,793
I just want to be on
my own for a while.

637
00:37:45,863 --> 00:37:47,262
[Birds chirping]

638
00:37:47,331 --> 00:37:49,663
Well,
you may have forgotten

639
00:37:49,734 --> 00:37:52,999
that you were once
a very sick little girl,

640
00:37:53,070 --> 00:37:54,935
but I haven't.

641
00:37:58,676 --> 00:38:01,941
All right.

642
00:38:02,013 --> 00:38:04,038
Do you think Juliet
could stay here

643
00:38:04,115 --> 00:38:05,776
while her parents
are away?

644
00:38:05,850 --> 00:38:07,249
Juliet's infectious.

645
00:38:07,318 --> 00:38:09,183
She'll be going
to the hospital.

646
00:38:09,253 --> 00:38:11,551
But she'll have no one
to look after her!

647
00:38:11,622 --> 00:38:13,715
Well, her parents won't
be going overseas now.

648
00:38:13,791 --> 00:38:16,885
They have to cancel
their trip.

649
00:38:16,961 --> 00:38:19,020
Don't worry about Juliet.

650
00:38:19,096 --> 00:38:20,154
[Smooches]

651
00:38:22,400 --> 00:38:23,731
[Hilda sighs]

652
00:38:23,801 --> 00:38:25,598
Well, it's not too late

653
00:38:25,670 --> 00:38:28,366
to cancel
our travel arrangements,

654
00:38:28,439 --> 00:38:30,304
if that's what you want.

655
00:38:30,374 --> 00:38:33,707
[Coughing in distance]

656
00:38:33,778 --> 00:38:36,975
I'm sure
you'll like it here.

657
00:38:37,048 --> 00:38:39,039
It's very tranquil.

658
00:38:39,116 --> 00:38:41,107
Oh, I've spoken
to the matron.

659
00:38:41,185 --> 00:38:43,983
She promises to take
extra special care of you.

660
00:38:44,055 --> 00:38:45,420
[Coughs]

661
00:38:45,489 --> 00:38:48,424
And you can carry on
with your studies

662
00:38:48,492 --> 00:38:50,050
while you convalesce.

663
00:38:50,127 --> 00:38:53,324
It's for the good
of your health, darling.

664
00:38:55,066 --> 00:38:58,263
Cheer up,
old thing, hmm?

665
00:38:58,336 --> 00:39:02,534
Four months...
fly by in no time.

666
00:39:06,143 --> 00:39:08,611
[Metal clanks, squeaking]

667
00:39:11,749 --> 00:39:13,876
[Coughing]

668
00:39:24,095 --> 00:39:26,290
[Crying]

669
00:39:31,969 --> 00:39:34,267
Honora; Juliet
won't be allowed visitors

670
00:39:34,338 --> 00:39:36,363
for at least
a couple of months, dear.

671
00:39:36,440 --> 00:39:39,170
I've booked you in
for a chest X-ray

672
00:39:39,243 --> 00:39:42,576
just to be
on the safe side.

673
00:39:42,646 --> 00:39:46,912
I thought I'd have a go
at building the birdhouse
on Saturday.

674
00:39:46,984 --> 00:39:49,111
Anybody
want to give me a hand?

675
00:39:51,122 --> 00:39:55,058
You used to love making
things with Dad, Yvonne.

676
00:39:55,126 --> 00:39:57,822
Pauline; This evening,
I had a brain wave

677
00:39:57,895 --> 00:40:00,728
that Juliet and I
should write to each other

678
00:40:00,798 --> 00:40:02,265
as Charles and Deborah.

679
00:40:02,333 --> 00:40:05,393
I wrote a six-page letter
as Charles

680
00:40:05,469 --> 00:40:08,131
and a two-page letter
as Paul.

681
00:40:08,205 --> 00:40:09,934
She has entered into

682
00:40:10,007 --> 00:40:12,407
the spirit of the thing
greatly.

683
00:40:14,478 --> 00:40:17,072
[Coughing]

684
00:40:17,148 --> 00:40:18,843
Juliet; "My dear Charles,

685
00:40:18,916 --> 00:40:21,908
"I miss you and adore you
in equal amounts

686
00:40:21,986 --> 00:40:25,217
"and long for the day
that we will be reunited.

687
00:40:25,289 --> 00:40:28,622
"But as I languish here
in this house of disease

688
00:40:28,692 --> 00:40:30,182
"and decrepitude,

689
00:40:30,261 --> 00:40:33,492
"my mind turns
with increasing frequency

690
00:40:33,564 --> 00:40:35,896
"to the problem of our son.

691
00:40:35,966 --> 00:40:37,661
"Although only 10,

692
00:40:37,735 --> 00:40:41,171
"Diello has thus far killed
57 people

693
00:40:41,238 --> 00:40:43,570
"and shows no desire to stop.

694
00:40:43,641 --> 00:40:45,632
It worries me, Charles."

695
00:40:45,709 --> 00:40:49,304
Pauline; "My dearest,
darling, Deborah,

696
00:40:49,380 --> 00:40:52,679
"affairs of state
continue to occupy my time.

697
00:40:52,750 --> 00:40:54,047
"I have to report

698
00:40:54,118 --> 00:40:57,485
"that the lower classes
are terrifically dull.

699
00:40:57,555 --> 00:40:59,887
"Only yesterday,

700
00:40:59,957 --> 00:41:03,757
"I was compelled to execute
several peasants

701
00:41:03,828 --> 00:41:06,854
"just to alleviate
the boredom.

702
00:41:06,931 --> 00:41:09,195
"Diello insisted
on coming along.

703
00:41:09,266 --> 00:41:11,291
"In fact,
he made such a fuss

704
00:41:11,368 --> 00:41:14,201
"that I had to let him
wield the ax himself.

705
00:41:14,271 --> 00:41:15,465
"Heads did roll...

706
00:41:15,539 --> 00:41:17,666
"not just the prisoners

707
00:41:17,741 --> 00:41:19,800
"but the royal guard,
my valet,

708
00:41:19,877 --> 00:41:21,674
"and several
unfortunate onlookers

709
00:41:21,745 --> 00:41:23,076
copped it as well."

710
00:41:23,147 --> 00:41:25,240
Juliet; "Oh, Charles,
I am despaired enough

711
00:41:25,316 --> 00:41:27,409
"to put Diello
in the hands of the cardinal

712
00:41:27,485 --> 00:41:29,476
"in the hope
that a good dose of religion

713
00:41:29,553 --> 00:41:31,646
will set the young chap
on the right path."

714
00:41:31,722 --> 00:41:33,587
Hello again.

715
00:41:35,893 --> 00:41:37,622
How are you getting on?

716
00:41:37,695 --> 00:41:39,424
It must be awfully hard

717
00:41:39,497 --> 00:41:42,193
being away
from your school chums.

718
00:41:42,266 --> 00:41:43,995
I've got something here

719
00:41:44,068 --> 00:41:47,401
that you might just like
to have a look at.

720
00:41:48,439 --> 00:41:51,374
Unfortunately, the miracles
of modern medicine

721
00:41:51,442 --> 00:41:55,276
can only go so far in
combating an illness
like TB.

722
00:41:55,346 --> 00:41:58,213
That's why I'm here,
because...

723
00:41:58,282 --> 00:41:59,715
[Voice fades]

724
00:41:59,783 --> 00:42:03,412
[Eerie music plays]

725
00:42:10,394 --> 00:42:12,259
Reach out, Juliet!

726
00:42:12,329 --> 00:42:14,524
Reach out for Jesus!

727
00:42:14,598 --> 00:42:15,656
Aah!

728
00:42:15,733 --> 00:42:17,132
[Crowd shouting]

729
00:42:17,201 --> 00:42:18,293
Aah!

730
00:42:18,369 --> 00:42:20,394
Aah! Aah!

731
00:42:20,471 --> 00:42:21,369
[Metal clangs]

732
00:42:21,438 --> 00:42:24,305
[Panting]

733
00:42:24,375 --> 00:42:26,809
Yvonne!

734
00:42:26,877 --> 00:42:28,310
Yvonne!

735
00:42:28,379 --> 00:42:31,815
[Panting]

736
00:42:31,882 --> 00:42:33,406
Paul!

737
00:42:33,484 --> 00:42:34,883
Paul!

738
00:42:34,952 --> 00:42:36,283
Oh!

739
00:42:36,353 --> 00:42:37,752
Oh!

740
00:42:37,821 --> 00:42:40,221
I'm so happy
to see you!

741
00:42:40,291 --> 00:42:44,284
Don't get too close.
She's still not 100%.

742
00:42:44,361 --> 00:42:45,828
Hello, Juliet.

743
00:42:45,896 --> 00:42:47,022
Hello!

744
00:42:47,097 --> 00:42:49,361
We brought you
some fruit.

745
00:42:49,433 --> 00:42:52,095
Oh, thank you so much!

746
00:42:52,169 --> 00:42:54,501
Your letters
are wonderful, Charles!

747
00:42:54,572 --> 00:42:57,006
Well, that's, um,
coming along nicely.

748
00:42:57,074 --> 00:43:00,237
Oh, I'm the matron's
favorite patient,

749
00:43:00,311 --> 00:43:03,371
and she showed me
her special stitch.

750
00:43:03,447 --> 00:43:05,608
I love the color.

751
00:43:05,683 --> 00:43:07,446
It's for you.

752
00:43:07,518 --> 00:43:08,951
Oh!

753
00:43:09,019 --> 00:43:12,580
[Both giggle]

754
00:43:14,658 --> 00:43:18,116
Goodness, me,
what a lot of letters.

755
00:43:18,195 --> 00:43:22,859
Ha. Are your parents
enjoying their trip?

756
00:43:22,933 --> 00:43:25,800
Oh, there's a couple
of unopened ones.

757
00:43:28,672 --> 00:43:31,004
I'm saving them
for a rainy day.

758
00:43:31,075 --> 00:43:34,340
- [Coughing in distance]
- I know it's hard for you
being in here,

759
00:43:34,411 --> 00:43:37,608
but it is for the good
of your health.

760
00:43:37,681 --> 00:43:39,444
They sent me off
to the Bahamas

761
00:43:39,516 --> 00:43:40,847
for the good of my health.

762
00:43:40,918 --> 00:43:43,318
They sent me off
to the Bay of bloody Islands

763
00:43:43,387 --> 00:43:44,820
for the good of my health!

764
00:43:48,292 --> 00:43:50,692
I'm sorry, Mrs. Rieper.

765
00:43:50,761 --> 00:43:53,855
I'm feeling
quite fatigued.

766
00:43:53,931 --> 00:43:57,526
Well, we don't want
to tire you out, dear.

767
00:43:57,601 --> 00:44:00,195
[Coughing in distance]

768
00:44:00,270 --> 00:44:03,205
Oh, can't you stay
a bit longer, Paul?

769
00:44:03,273 --> 00:44:06,731
No, we've got a tram
to catch, Yvonne.

770
00:44:17,454 --> 00:44:19,115
Bye.

771
00:44:28,032 --> 00:44:30,592
You know,
this is quite something.

772
00:44:30,668 --> 00:44:32,226
You're damn clever.

773
00:44:33,804 --> 00:44:36,568
So, Deborah
is married to Charles,

774
00:44:36,640 --> 00:44:40,337
and this chap Nicholas
is her tennis instructor?

775
00:44:40,411 --> 00:44:42,845
Yes, but there's
nothing between them.

776
00:44:42,913 --> 00:44:45,347
Deborah would never
go for a commoner.

777
00:44:45,416 --> 00:44:46,678
[Sighs]

778
00:44:46,750 --> 00:44:49,014
Nicholas has got
his eye on Gina,

779
